               <head>Inshirāḥ-i Sharafnāmah-ʼi Sikandarī by Amān Allāh Amānī</head>
               <msContents class="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh2010105563">
                  <summary>A Persian commentary on the <title>Sharafnāmah</title>, the first part of
                     the <title>Iskandarnāmah</title>, by <persName role="ant" key="VIAF_2474895"
                        >Niẓāmī Ganjavī</persName>, (d. 1202-03) composed by one Amānī whom Storey
                     identifies with Amān Allāh Amānī, entitled Khānahzād Khān Fīrūz Jang. The work
                     begins with a preface in verse before interpreting the
                        <title>Iskandarnāmah</title> in conventional prose. In the preface, the
                     author states that the work was commissioned by the Mughal emperor <persName
                        role="pat" key="VIAF_38320916">Jahangir</persName> (r.1605-27), and gives
                     the date of composition with the <hi rend="italic">abjad</hi> chronogram "<hi
                        rend="italic">āghāz-i vay</hi>" equating to 1025/1616. </summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Uk_Delhi_Persian_1245-item1">
                     <author key="person_f364">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Amān Allāh Khān Zamān Fīrūz Jang Amānī </persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa"> امان الله خان زمان فیروز جنگ امانی</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_23475">Inshirāḥ-i Sharafnāmah-ʼi
                        Sikandarī</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa">انشراح شرفنامۀ سکندری</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa"> بنام خداوند مشکل‌گشای / بتاریکی لفظ معنی‌نمای</incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa">بجلباب دانش و بینش خود پوشند </explicit>
                     <colophon>(f. 85r) Completed on 7 Zu ʼl-Ḥijjah 1258 AH (9 January 1843). </colophon>
                     <note>
                        <p>The title and the author's name appear in the scribe's colophon and not
                           in the work itself. </p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
